'''Becky Morgan''',born in [[Abergavenny]] on [[5 September]] 1974 is a [[Wales|Welsh]] [[professional golfer]] who plays mainly on the U.S. based [[LPGA Tour]] but is also a member of the [[Ladies European Tour]]

==Amateur Career==

Becky Morgan was introduced to the game of golf by her grandfather when she was 12<ref name="Age12"> 
{{cite web
  | title = Becky Morgan - View from a Star
  | publisher = City and County of Swansea
  | url = http://www.swansea.gov.uk/index.cfm?articleid=12834
  | accessdate = 2007-03-27 }}</ref> and had a successful amateur career. She was a member of the Welsh Junior and Under-21 teams and also won the 1991 and 1992 Welsh School Championship titles.<ref name="LPGABio"> 
{{cite web
  | title = Becky Morgan Full Career Bio
  | publisher = LPGA
  | url = http://www.lpga.com/content/2007PlayerBiosPDF/Morgan-07.pdf
  | accessdate = 2007-03-28}}</ref> She was a member of the Great Britain and Ireland [[Curtis Cup]] Team in 1998 and 2000<ref name="Curtis1"> 
{{cite web
  | title = Previous Matches 1932-2002
  | publisher = USGA
  | url = http://www.curtiscup.org/2004/history/previous_matches.html
  | accessdate = 2007-03-27 }}</ref> and a member of the Vagliano Trophy team in 1997 and 1999. Morgan was the runner-up in 1996 and a semifinalist in 1997 at the [[British Ladies Amateur Golf Championship|British Amateur Championship]]. She was 2nd at the British Strokeplay championship in 1998.<ref name="LETBio"> 
{{cite web
  | title = Becky Morgan Player Profile
  | publisher = LET
  | url = http://www.ladieseuropeantour.info/profiles/101040.htm
  | accessdate = 2007-03-27 }}</ref> <ref name="LPGABio"/>

She enrolled at [[University of North Carolina at Greensboro]] in 1994,<ref name="Cpoauk"> 
{{cite web
  | title = College Prospects of America UK Clients
  | publisher = USGA
  | url = http://www.cpoauk.com/success.htm 
  | accessdate = 2007-03-27 }}</ref> and during the next four years won 10 NCAA div 1 medallist titles, including three [[Big South Conference]] Championships from 1995-1997 resulting in her being named Big South All-American for those three years.<ref name="BigSouth"> 
{{cite web
  | title = Big South All-Time All-Americans
  | publisher = Big South Sports
  | url = http://www.bigsouthsports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=4800&KEY=&ATCLID=131007 
  | accessdate = 2007-03-27 }}</ref> She finished 10th in the NCAA Championship in 1997, the year she graduated with a major in Geography.<ref name="LPGABio"/>

Morgan returned to Wales and continued her amateur career finishing runner-up at the Welsh Amateur Championship from 1998-99<ref name="LETBio"/> and second at the South Atlantic Amateur Championship in 2000.<ref name="Atlantic"> 
{{cite web
  | title = South Atlantic Ladies Amateur
  | publisher = GolfWeek
  | url = http://www.golfweekrankings.com/scores/2000/amateur/women/2389.asp
  | accessdate = 2007-03-27 }}</ref>

==Professional Career==

Morgan turned professional in August 2000. She qualified for the [[Ladies European Tour]] by finishing tied for sixth at the LET Qualifying School<ref name="LETBio"/> and earned non-exempt status on the [[LPGA Tour]] by finishing T14th at the LPGA Final Qualifying Tournament<ref name="LPGABio"/> and thus had rookie seasons on both sides of the Atlantic in 2001.

She played in eight events on LET in 2001 without missing a cut, posting four top tens<ref name="LETBio"/> including narrowly losing the French Open to Norway's Suzann Pettersen at the third play off hole.<ref name="French"> 
{{cite web
  | title = Pettersen defends in France
  | publisher = LET
  | date = 2002-06-19
  | url = http://www.ladieseuropeantour.com/content/let_content_news.php?Id=4580
  | accessdate = 2007-03-28}}</ref> She also played 16 events on the LPGA earning her first LPGA top 10 finish with a tie for 7th at the Longs Drugs Challenge. She finished second to Hee-Won Han for Louise Suggs Rolex Rookie of the Year honours.<ref name="LPGABio"/>

In 2002 she competed in four events on the Evian Ladies European Tour, where she posted two top-10 finishes. She also played 18 events on the LPGA with a T7 at the ShopRite LPGA Classic being her only top ten finish. In 2003, she finished second at the ShopRite LPGA Classic, the best LPGA finish of her career and in 23 starts had seven top tens. Becky played in six events on the LET with her best finish being a tie for fourth at the HP Open. She narrowly missed out on a captain's pick for the [[2003 Solheim Cup]].<ref name="EUR2"> 
{{cite web
  | title = European Team announced
  | publisher = LET
  | date = 2003-08-25
  | url = http://www.ladieseuropeantour.com/content/let_content_news.php?Id=4249&page=101	
  | accessdate = 2007-03-18 }}</ref>

In 2004 Becky played most of the year on the LPGA. In 24 starts, Becky amassed three top tens. She also played in four events on the LET with her best finish being 3rd at the HP Open in Sweden. She also concentrated on the LPGA for 2005 and recorded 1 top tens out of 23 events played. Her best performance on the LET was a tie for sixth on home soil at the Wales Ladies Championship.

She teamed up with [[Becky Brewerton]] to finish 6th in the inaugural [[Women's World Cup of Golf]] in 2005. They teamed up again in 2006 when they finished third<ref name="WWCG2006"> 
{{cite web
  | title = Beckys are third in the world
  | publisher = WLGU
  | url = http://wlgu.org/Summer%2006.pdf 
  | accessdate = 2007-03-27 }}</ref> and 2007 when they finished eighth.<ref name="ICWales"> 
{{cite web
  | title = Sports round-up Golf: World Cup victory
  | publisher = South Wales Echo
  | date = 2007-01-22
  | url = http://icwales.icnetwork.co.uk/0700sports/1200sportsroundup/tm_headline=golf--world-cup-victory&method=full&objectid=18514317&siteid=50082-name_page.html 
  | accessdate = 2007-03-27 }}</ref>


